definition.value: A mannosyl group derived from 4-O-sulfo-N-acetyl-beta-D-galactosaminyl-(1->4)-N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosaminyl-(1->2)-alpha-D-mannose.

A monosaccharide derivative that is (R)-isoflavan substituted by a hydroxy group substituted at position 2', methoxy groups at positions 3' and 4' and a beta-D-glucopyranosyloxy group at position 7 respectively.
An N-acetyl-D-glucosaminyl group derived from 3-O-sulfo-beta-D-glucuronosyl-(1->3)-beta-D-galactosyl-(1->4)-beta-D-glucosamine
An N-acetyl-D-glucosaminyl group derived from beta-D-glucuronosyl-(1->3)-beta-D-galactosyl-(1->4)-beta-D-glucosamine.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycerol in which the acyl groups at positions 1 and 2 are specified as (9Z,12Z)-octadecadienoyl and octadecanoyl respectively.
A 3-hydroxy-fatty acyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxy group of 3-hydroxydecanoic acid.
Any imidazolidine-2,4-dione that bears a single substituent at position 5 and has D-configuration.
Any imidazolidine-2,4-dione that bears a single substituent at position 5 and has L-configuration.
A racemate comprising equal amounts of (3R,4R)- and (3S,4S)-A2-32-01.
A racemate comprising equal amounts of (3R,4R)- and (3S,4S)-A2-58-06.
A N-acylpyrrolidine that is proline substituted by a propanoyl group at the nitrogen atom.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which the acyl groups at positions 1 and 2 are pentadecanoyl and (5Z,8Z,11Z,14Z)-eicosatetraenoyl respectively.
A hydrate that is the hexahydrate form of magnesium dichloride.
A diacylglycerol 34:1 in which the acyl groups specified at positions 1 and 2 are (11Z)-octadecenoyl and hexadecanoyl respectively.
A  hydroxybutyric acid substituted by hydroxy groups at positions 2 and 3 respectively.
A omega-hydroxy fatty acid that is butyric acid substituted by hydroxy groups at positions 2 and 4 respectively.
A glutamic acid derivative that is glutamic acid substituted by a carbamoyl group at the nitrogen atom.
A pentonic acid that is the 2-deoxy derivative of D-ribonic acid.
A 2'-deoxycytidine phosphate that is 2'-deoxycytidine-5'-triphosphate in which the hydrogen at position 5 on the cytosine ring is replaced by iodine.
A member of the class of ribonates that is the  conjugate base of 2-deoxy-D-ribonic acid.
An alpha,beta-unsaturated monocarboxylic acid that is  acrylic acid substituted by a hydroxy group at position 2.
A hydrate that is the monohydrate form of magnesium dichloride.
A hydrate that is the dihydrate form of manganese(II) sulfate.
A hydrate that is the tetrahydrate form of manganese(II) sulfate.
A gluconic acid having L-configuration.
A metal sulfate in which the metal component is manganese in the +2 oxidation state.

An N-acetyl-D-glucosaminyl group derived from N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosaminyl-(1->4)-N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosamine. A disaccharide group formed from the hydrolysis of chitin (a linear polymer of repeated GlcNAc units)

An N-acetyl-D-glucosaminyl group derived from N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosaminyl-(1->4)-N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosaminyl-(1->4)-N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosamine. A trisaccharide group formed from the hydrolysis of chitin (a linear polymer of repeated GlcNAc units).
A  ketogluconic acid that is L-gluconic acid in which the hydroxy group at position 2 has been oxidized to a keto group.
A hydrate that is the monohydrate form of manganese(II) sulfate.
A 3-oxo monocarboxylic acid that is valeric acid substituted by a methyl group at position 2 and a keto group at position 3.
A N-acylglycine that is glycine substituted by a 2-methylbutanoyl group at the N atom.
A tetritol that is  erythritol substituted by a methyl group at position 2.
A hydrate that is the tetrahydrate form of manganese(II) chloride.
A dihydroxy monocarboxylic acid that is 3-hydroxypropanoic acid substituted by a 3-hydroxyphenyl group at position 3.
A hydrochloride obtained by combining the free base of neutral red with one equivalent of hydrochloric acid. Neutral red acts as a pH indicator, changing from red to yellow between pH 6.8 and 8.0.
A omega-hydroxy fatty acid that is butyric acid substituted by hydroxy groups at positions 3 and 4 respectively.

A member of the class of phenazines carrying methyl, amino and dimethylamino substituents at positions 2, 3 and 7 respectively. The free base of neutral red, which acts as a pH indicator, changing from red to yellow between pH 6.8 and 8.0.
An organic cation obtained by protonation of neutral red free base.
A member of the class of indanones that is indane-1,3-dione bearing two additional hydroxy substituents at position 2.
A hexadecenoyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxy group of (11Z)-hexadec-11-enoic acid.
An unsaturated fatty acyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxy group of (10E,12Z)-hexadecadienoic acid.
An androstanoid with a 5beta-configuration formed by reduction across the C4-C5 double bond of epitestosterone.
A 3beta-hydroxycholest-5-en-26-oic acid in which the stereocentre at position 25 has R-configuration.
Lipid IVA glycosylated with three 3-deoxy-D-manno-octulosonic acid (KDO) residues.
A 9,11,13-octadecatrienoic acid having its double bonds in cis, trans and cis configurations, respectively. It has been isolated from  pomegranate (Punica granatum).
An ammonium ion resulting from the protonation of the nitrogen of amorolfine.
A 3-oxo-5beta-steroid formed from corticosterone by reduction across the C4-C5 double bond.
